     ============================================ -->
<section class="section-white" aria-labelledby="faq-heading">
  <div class="container-7xl">

    <div class="text-center mb-12">
      <div class="accent-bar"></div>
      <h2 class="h2" id="faq-heading">Technical Q&amp;A for Facility Managers</h2>
      <p style="font-size:17px; color:var(--gray-600); margin-top:14px; max-width:680px; margin-left:auto; margin-right:auto;">
        The questions engineers, operations directors, and property managers ask us most — answered with the specificity your facility decisions require.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-list">

      <article class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">What NADCA standard does Southeast Commercial Services follow for commercial duct cleaning?</div>
        <p class="faq-a">We adhere to the NADCA ACR (Assessment, Cleaning, and Restoration) standard — the industry benchmark that defines acceptable cleanliness levels for HVAC systems in commercial and industrial buildings. Every project includes pre- and post-cleaning assessments to confirm compliance with ACR surface contamination thresholds.</p>
      </article>

      <article class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Why does it matter that your technicians are in-house rather than subcontracted?</div>
        <p class="faq-a">Subcontracted labor creates accountability gaps — inconsistent training, variable equipment quality, and no continuity of standards from job to job. Our in-house technicians are full-time employees trained exclusively in commercial and industrial duct systems. They carry our insurance, follow our safety protocols, and are held to our quality benchmarks on every project.</p>
      </article>

      <article class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">How do you minimize operational disruption during duct cleaning in an active facility?</div>
        <p class="faq-a">We conduct a pre-project site walk to map access points, duct zones, and operational constraints. Work is phased to address one air handling unit zone at a time. For mission-critical facilities — hospitals, data centers, 24-hour manufacturing — we schedule all work during planned maintenance windows, nights, or weekends to eliminate production impact.</p>
      </article>

      <article class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">What equipment do you use for large-scale industrial duct cleaning in Atlanta?</div>
        <p class="faq-a">For industrial ductwork we deploy truck-mounted and portable high-capacity negative air machines (up to 16,000 CFM), HEPA-filtered vacuum extraction units, pneumatic rotary brush systems, and compressed air whip/skipper ball tools — sized and selected specifically for the duct diameter, layout, and contamination type at your facility.</p>
      </article>

      <article class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Do you provide documentation for compliance and insurance purposes after a duct cleaning project?</div>
        <p class="faq-a">Yes. Every completed project receives a written post-cleaning report documenting the systems cleaned, methodology used, NADCA compliance status, and any observations about duct condition that may require remediation. This documentation supports facility compliance records, insurance requirements, and LEED or IAQ audit trails.</p>
      </article>

      <article class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Can Southeast Commercial Services handle kitchen exhaust and grease duct cleaning in addition to HVAC ductwork?</div>
        <p class="faq-a">Yes. We clean commercial kitchen exhaust systems, grease duct lines, and hood assemblies in restaurants, hotel kitchens, institutional cafeterias, and food manufacturing facilities — following NFPA 96 standards for grease removal and fire prevention compliance. Both HVAC and kitchen exhaust services are executed by our same in-house team.</p>
      </article>

    </div>

  </div>
</section>


